
Dependency sorting operates only on top-level declaration headers and header-provided dependency edges.

It makes declarations linearly consumable by AST.
It doesn't look into executable bodies.
It doesn't fix missing header edges by doing semantic work late.

## Main path

`src/compiler_frontend/module_dependencies.rs`

## What dependency sorting owns

Dependency sorting owns:

- topological sorting of parsed top-level declaration headers
- cycle detection in the strict top-level declaration graph
- missing header-provided dependency diagnostics
- source-order stability among otherwise independent declarations
- finalising `ModuleSymbols.declarations` in sorted order
- appending builtin declarations
- appending the implicit entry `start` header after sorted declarations

It doesn't use executable function/start body references.
It doesn't use body-local declarations.

## Constants

Constant initializer references are top-level compile-time declaration dependencies.
They are not body references.
They belong in the header dependency graph.

Dependency sorting orders constants using header-provided constant initializer dependency edges.
Same-file constants keep source-order semantics.
Same-file forward references are rejected.
Cross-file constant cycles are dependency cycles.

Same-file symbol hints that don't materialise as headers are not always dependency-sort errors.
When a hint looks like a same-file declaration reference but no graph header exists, Stage 3 defers to AST type/expression resolution so the later stage can report the more precise semantic diagnostic.

## Facades

Module-root facades, `#mod.bst` files that belong to a project module root, participate in dependency sorting like other top-level declaration providers.

They remain boundary export layers for visibility.
They are still declarations.
Public authored declarations, public re-exports, exported constants and exported type surfaces must be ordered before declarations in outside modules that import them through the facade.

Other files inside the same module should not depend on symbols declared directly inside the module-root facade.
Header import visibility enforces that boundary.
Dependency sorting should not make facade-private implementation details look like normal local dependencies.

## Source libraries

Source-library facades, such as builder-provided `@html`, also participate in dependency sorting.
Their declarations are first-class providers to the consuming module, not opaque blobs.

Because source libraries have no outgoing dependency edges to project files, the topological sort naturally places them before project files that import them.

Source-library facade export edges may use the public import path rather than the concrete `#mod.bst` header path.
Stage 3 treats those as satisfied facade-export edges, not as new graph nodes.
This lets public source-library API names order consumers without leaking facade filesystem identity into the dependency graph.

## Header/dependency/AST contract

Header parsing and dependency sorting are responsible for making top-level declarations linearly consumable by AST.

After dependency sorting:

- AST receives headers in dependency order.
- AST doesn't topologically sort constants, structs, choices, functions or aliases again.
- AST must not rediscover top-level declarations from raw file tokens.
- AST must not rebuild file import visibility from scratch.
- AST resolves declaration shells in sorted order, then parses executable bodies against the completed environment.
- The implicit entry `start` header is never a dependency participant and is always emitted after sorted declarations.

AST may register nominal identity and generic parameter metadata before constants so constructors are name-resolvable.
Unresolved field and variant constructor shells stay in AST-owned side tables until semantic `TypeId`s are checked and final member definitions are written to `TypeEnvironment`.

## Feature rule

If AST needs a top-level declaration to be resolved before another declaration, that dependency belongs in the header dependency graph.

If a new feature introduces a top-level dependency, add it to header parsing and dependency sorting.
Don't add another AST ordering pass.

That shortcut seems convenient once.
Then the compiler has two declaration-order systems forever.

